analysis: The documents all relate to the designation of international organizations as public international organizations, granting them certain privileges, exemptions, and immunities under the International Organizations Immunities Act. The organizations span various sectors, including telecommunications, health, volunteer services, refugee assistance, fisheries, law, education, science, culture, civil aviation, finance, and anti-corruption. The documents also ensure that existing or future privileges acquired through treaties or congressional actions are not affected.
title: International Organizations' Privileges and Immunities
